{% extends "layouts/doc-layout" %}

{% block title %}Sort Filter - Wisp Template Documentation{% end %}

{% block body %}
<h1>Sort Filter</h1>

<p>Sorts an array in ascending order. All elements are compared as strings.</p>

<h2>Syntax</h2>
<pre><code>{% raw %}
{% .array | sort %}
{% endraw %}</code></pre>

<h2>Examples</h2>
<pre><code>{% raw %}
{% assign words = "banana,apple,cherry" | split: "," %}
{% for w in words | sort %}{{ w }} {% end %}
{% endraw %}</code></pre>
<p><strong>Output:</strong> apple banana cherry</p>
<p>Strings are sorted in ascending lexicographic (alphabetical) order.</p>

<pre><code>{% raw %}
{% assign nums = "10,9,2,1,20" | split: "," %}
{% for n in nums | sort %}{{ n }} {% end %}
{% endraw %}</code></pre>
<p><strong>Output:</strong> 1 10 2 20 9</p>
<p>Numbers in a string array are sorted as strings, not numerically. In string order, <code>"10"</code> comes before <code>"2"</code> because <code>"1"</code> &lt; <code>"2"</code> lexicographically.</p>

<pre><code>{% raw %}
{% assign tags = .article.tags | sort %}
{% for tag in tags %}<span>{{ tag }}</span>{% end %}
{% endraw %}</code></pre>
<p>Sort a variable-length list before rendering it for consistent output.</p>

<h2>Notes</h2>
<ul>
  <li>All values are converted to strings before comparison, so sorting is always lexicographic (string order), not numeric.</li>
  <li>Sort order is ascending (A → Z, 0 → 9 as strings).</li>
  <li>The original array is not modified; a new sorted array is returned.</li>
  <li>To sort numerically, convert values to numbers before sorting or handle ordering in your Go data layer.</li>
</ul>

<h2>See Also</h2>
<ul>
  <li><a href="/docs/filters/reverse">reverse</a></li>
  <li><a href="/docs/filters/uniq">uniq</a></li>
</ul>
{% end %}
